title: Automated License Plate Readers (Antioch California Police Department)

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Automated License Plate Readers (Antioch California Police Department)
communications.communication:
Dear Custodian of Records:

This letter constitutes a request under the California Public Records Act ("CPRA") from the Electronic Frontier Foundation, submitted with the assistance of MuckRock News. 

We request the following records related to Automated License Plate Readers ("ALPRs") and your law enforcement agency ("Agency").

Part A - Information related to ALPR data sharing.

A1. The names of agencies and organizations with which the Agency shares ALPR data;
A2. The names of agencies and organizations from which the Agency receives ALPR data;
A3. The names of agencies and organizations with which the Agency shares “hot list” information;
A4. The names of agencies and organizations from which the Agency receives “hot list” information.
The information requested in items A1-A4 is readily available for extraction through the ALPR software you use. For example, with Vigilant Solutions/Motorola Solutions, this data can be exported easily using the Data Sharing Report function. With Flock Safety, this information is available through the transparency portal function. Other software, such as BOSS, has similar functionality.  

Most agencies have encountered little difficulty in providing this information (see below). In a small number of cases, an agency has interpreted items A1-A4 as requesting the creation of a record that does not exist. We disagree: this data is maintained by your software, can be exported through software your agency has already purchased, and is therefore subject to CPRA. 

However, should you disagree, you may alternatively produce the following records:  

A5. All agreements, memoranda of understanding, requests, or other certifying documents that external agencies have signed to comply with Sec 1798.90.52(b) for accessing your agency's ALPR data. These documents are also often required under the "Releasing ALPR Data" subsection of a California law enforcement agency's SB 34 policy. 
A6. All agreements, memoranda of understanding, requests, or other certifying documents  that your agency has signed pursuant to Sec 1798.90.52(b) to access other agencies' ALPR data.
A7. All "records of access" required by Sec. 1798.90.52(a) for the periods January 1, 2021 until the date of processing this request. 

Items A5-A7 are not necessary if your agency provides the information requested in items A1-A4. We feel that items A1-A4 are more focused and would require less labor from your agency to produce. 

Part B - Information Related to Numbers of “Detections” (plate scans) and “Hits” (plate scans that matched to a hotlist)

B1. The aggregate number of "detections" collected during 2023.
B2.  The aggregate number of “hits” during 2023.

The information requested in items B1-B2 is readily available through the ALPR software you use. For example, with Vigilant Solutions/Motorola Solutions, this data can be exported easily using the Hit Ratio Report function. With Flock Safety, this information  is available through the transparency portal function. Other software, such as BOSS, has similar functionality.  As noted above, this information exists within your system and can be easily exported with existing software.

Part C - Assistance, Description, and Recommendations. 

We make the following requests under section 6253.1 of the California Public Records Act

C1. A description of  the information technology and physical location in which the records exist.
C2. Assist us identifying records and information that will help the public understand how ALPR data and hotlists are shared, how much data is collected year-to-year, and how much of that data matches a hot list; and 
C3. Provide suggestions for overcoming any practical basis for denying access to the information sought.

Please note that your agency provided substantially similar data in 2022. 

CPRA requires you to undertake reasonable efforts to locate responsive records and to work in good faith with requesters to respond to their request. See CYAC v. City of National City, 220 Cal.App.4th 1385, 1430 (2013). Thus under the CPRA you are obligated to conduct a reasonable search and cannot deny a request merely because it might generate a large volume of records. 

We ask that you please respond to this request within 10 days either by providing all the requested records or by providing a written response setting forth the legal authority on which you rely in withholding or redacting any document, as well as stating when documents will be made available. Should you choose to withhold or reject this request, we ask that you provide an explanation of why your agency is responding differently compared to the many others that have complied with our request. 

We also request that any records maintained in an electronic format be provided in that same format (such as a PDF, CSV or XLS file), to avoid copying costs.

However, should you be unable to do so, EFF will reimburse you for the direct costs of copying these records (if you elect to charge for copying) plus postage. If you anticipate that these costs will exceed $25.00, or that the time needed to copy the records will delay their release, please contact me so that I can arrange to inspect the documents or decide which documents I wish to have copied. Please also provide an invoice and a cost breakdown of the fee estimate. If the fees are less than $25.00, please copy and send the records and invoice as soon as possible, and we will promptly pay the required costs.

Thank you for your consideration of this request. If you have any questions or concerns, or if I can provide any clarification that will help identify responsive documents or focus this request, please do not hesitate to contact me at (415) 436-9333 x151 or dm@eff.org. You may also mail correspondence to the Electronic Frontier Foundation, 815 Eddy. St. San Francisco, CA, 94109.
                                               
Sincerely,
 
 
Dave Maass
Director of Investigations
Electronic Frontier Foundation

communications.subject: Re: [24-19722] Freedom of Information Act Request - Katie King
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. King,

This is in response to your Freedom of Information Act dated January 24,
2024. Your request was received in this office on August 15, 2023 with the
assigned control number 24-19722.

Specifically, you seek documents related to the murder of the Reverend
Willie G. Lee in Belzoni, Mississippi on May 7, 1955.

We searched in Record Group 60, General Records of the Department of
Justice. Specifically, we searched in the Department of
Justice General Index to Litigation Files
<https://catalog.archives.gov/id/1882794> (Entry A1 110-A) and found a
card responsive
to your request regarding Willie G. Lee with the assigned Case File #
144-41-210 . However, the files are subject to *access restrictions* and
need to be reviewed for categories of information exempted from disclosure
under the Freedom of Information Act (FOIA). I have included  our
Special Access/FOIA Office (specialaccess_foia@nara.gov) on this email to
review the records and to conduct a search for additional FBI records. They
will respond separately to your request.. Here is the citation for your
reference:

*Record Group 60*
*General Records of the Department of Justice*

*Class 144 (Civil Rights) Litigation Case Files*
*Entry A1-COR 144*
*Box 2992@ B190/26/23/6*

We have also identified additional case file numbers 144-41-210 and
144-40-2154 that were responsive to your request. However, they are not in
the custody of the National Archives. If you wish to access them you will
need to file a FOIA request directly with the Department of Justice. You
may submit your request at  <http://goog_538679821/>
https://www.justice.gov/oip/make-foia-request-doj

We have also searched in the Index Cards to Classification 44 (Civil
Rights) Headquarters Case Files, 1923-1972
<https://catalog.archives.gov/id/2387379> for any reference to a case file
for Willie G. Lee but there were no responsive results.

We do not consider this a denial of your FOIA request. However, if you are
not satisfied with our action on this request, your options for appeal and
dispute resolution are outlined in the attached enclosure. If you have any
questions, you may reach us at archives2reference@nara.gov.



This completes the processing of your request.



Sincerely,

Michael J. Hancock

Archives Specialist

Textual Reference at Archives II (RR2RR)

The National Archives at College Park

8601 Adelphi Rd College Park, MD 20740

michaelj.hancock1@nara.gov
-- 

Michael J. Hancock

Archives Specialist

Textual Reference at Archives II (RR2RR)

The National Archives at College Park

8601 Adelphi Rd College Park, MD 20740

michaelj.hancock1@nara.gov

title: Shotspotter Data (East Palo Alto Police Department)

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Shotspotter Data (East Palo Alto Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1) A list, database, or comparable record of every alert that has been generated by the department's Shotspotter technology since time of implementation through December 31st, 2020 or the date at which Shotspotter was deactivated-whichever date comes first. For instance, if Shotspotter was implemented in the city on January 1, 2008, I would like all Shotspotter data from this date to December 31st, 2020. The list/database should include, where possible, the date, time, location (address or latitude+longitude coordinates), single or multiple shot distinction, whether the shots were confirmed, police district located, and associated case number for each alert.
2) Any document that provides information on the procedure for how  the police department should respond to Shotspotter alerts. In particular, I am looking for a document that describes how the police will react to a Shotspotter alert. For instance, if an alert is created, are police dispatched?
3) Shotspotter rollout dates. If the police department rolled out the Shotspotter data by police district, please include the implementation dates attached to each police district.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Michael Topper

title: Public Records Request for Data on School Policing (Holliston Police Department)

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Public Records Request for Data on School Policing (Holliston Police Department)
communications.communication:
To whoever it may concern: 

This letter constitutes a request pursuant to the Public Records Act, G.L. c.66, §10, for public records in the custody of your school district. Under the Criminal Justice Reform Act,  school districts and law enforcement agencies must “specify the manner and division of responsibility for collecting and reporting the school-based arrests, citations and court referrals of students to the Department of Elementary and Secondary Education” (DESE).   DESE began collecting data on school-related arrests in the 2018-19 school year. In the 2019-20 school year, DESE has expanded that collection to include data on all referrals to law enforcement.  DESE has defined these terms as follows, borrowing the same definitions used by the U.S. Department of Education since its 2009 Civil Rights Data Collection.  

A school-related arrest “[r]efers to an arrest of a student for any activity conducted on school grounds, during off campus school activities (including while taking school transportation), or due to a referral by any school official. All school-related arrests are considered referrals to law enforcement.”  

A referral to law enforcement “[i]s an action by which a student is reported to any law enforcement agency or official, including a school police unit, for an incident that occurs on school grounds, during school-related events, or while taking school transportation, regardless of whether official action is taken. Citations, tickets, court referrals, and school-related arrests are considered referrals to law enforcement.”   


I request the following public records, as defined in G. L. c. 4, § 7 (twenty-sixth): 

1.	An extract of your records management system or database that includes each school-related arrest and each referral to law enforcement conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022 school year (up until the day the records are produced). Specifically, we request an extract of the database to include the following columns:
a.	Date of arrest or referral to law enforcement
b.	Time of arrest or referral to law enforcement
c.	Charge (or charges)
d.	Whether the individual(s) was arrested or referred to law enforcement
e.	Sex of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
f.	Age of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
g.	Race of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
h.	Ethnicity of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
i.	Disability status of the individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
j.	Whether the individual arrested or referred to law enforcement is a student at the school.
k.	Name of arresting officer, if applicable, and 
l.	Badge number of the arresting officer or the officer that referred the youth to law enforcement, as applicable.

2.	If such an extract of the database in question 1 is not possible, please provide school incident reports on each school-related arrest and referral to law enforcement conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022 school year (up until the day the records are produced). 

3.	A copy of any active standard operating procedures developed with the police department and/or other law enforcement agencies regarding police placement or activity in your corresponding school;  and,

4.	Any records instructing or informing police personnel of, or otherwise describing data reporting requirements and procedures for complying with G.L. c. 71 § 37P(b).

5.	The cost to the school district of assigning a school resource officer to each school; and, 

6.	The total number of school resource officers and total number of guidance counselors for each school in your district for school years 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and,

7.	The total number and a brief description of 911 calls from schools in your district to local police departments conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022, and, 

8.	A description of the proposed budget for mental, social, or emotional health support personnel for the school district.

As this request involves a matter of public interest and will not be used for any commercial purpose, we ask that all fees associated with this request be waived pursuant to 950 C.M.R. 32.07(2)(k). The purpose of this request is to determine whether your school district and police department are complying with their reporting obligations under the Criminal Justice Reform Act.  “The public has an interest in knowing whether public servants are carrying out their duties in an efficient and law-abiding manner.”    

It would be ill-advised to impose a fee for data that your school district may have failed to report in violation of statutory and regulatory duty.  Moreover, as you know, municipalities with a population of over 20,000 may not assess a fee for the first 2 hours of time spent searching for, compiling, segregating, redacting and reproducing a requested record. Finally, pursuant to 950 C.M.R. 32.07(2)(i), a records access officer shall assess no fee greater than the lowest hourly rate of a person capable of compiling, segregating, redacting and reproducing a requested record. In the event that a charge is incurred for this request which you will not waive, please so indicate and include an itemization of estimated good faith costs.
 
Please provide public records to a requestor in an electronic format unless the record is not available in an electronic format. G.L.c. 66, § 6A(d). 

The Public Records Act requires that you comply with this request within ten (10) business days following receipt. If you believe that documents or data responsive to any request herein is not public record and thus not subject to disclosure, please set forth in writing the specific reasons for such assertion, including the specific exemption or exemptions that you believe apply.  To the extent that you determine that records need to be redacted in order to be produced under any law protecting the privacy of named individuals, please do so rather than withholding them in their entirety.

If you have any questions about this request, or need additional time to respond, please contact me by phone at (617)-373-5862 or by email at k.stathulis@northeastern.edu. Thank you in advance for your prompt response to this request.
	
Sincerely, 


Katherine Stathulis, Esq.
Center for Public Interest, Advocacy, and Collaboration
Northeastern University School of Law

communications.subject: RE: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Public Records Request for Data on School Policing (Holliston Police Department)
communications.communication:
Good afternoon,

I am reaching out on behalf of Katherine Stathulis to let you know that she received your message. She was unable to get through on the phone number provided, but wanted to acknowledge your request. Heather Atherton

Northeastern University School of Law

Dear Attorney Katherine Stathulis, 

We have compiled the records you requested and have attached them to this reply. 

Please be advised that pursuant to 950 CMR 32.00 and G.L. c. 66, section 10A(a) you have the right to appeal this decision to the Supervisor of Public Records within 90 calendar days. Such appeal shall be in writing, and shall include a copy of the letter by which the request was made and, if available, a copy of the letter by which the custodian responded. The Supervisor shall accept an appeal only from a person who had made his or her record request in writing. Pursuant to G.L. c. 66, section 10A(c), you also have the right to seek judicial review by commencing a civil action in the superior court.

Should you have any questions, please do not hesitate to contact me.

communications.subject: RE: New York Freedom of Information Law Request #R000103-061223
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

This is an appeal of SCOC's determination on January 16, 2024 -- following similar determinations on December 14, 2023; November 13, 2023; October 13, 2023; September 12, 2023; and August 14, 2023 -- regarding request R000103-061223.

SCOC has constructively denied my request. Seven months of repeated delays are unreasonable given the narrow scope of the request. Considering similar requests I've had fulfilled by SCOC, I anticipate this one to result in well under 100 pages of mostly boilerplate releasable records.

Because of this appeal, SCOC is required by law to, within 10 business days, provide specific reasons why this request cannot be fulfilled, or else must provide the records sought.

According to the Committee on Open Government, if a government entity acknowledges that a request has been received, but has failed to grant access by 
the specific date given beyond 20 business days, or if the specific date given is  unreasonable, a request may be considered to have been constructively denied. In such a circumstance, the denial may be appealed in accordance with Public Officers Law §89.4(a), which states in relevant part that:

“...any person denied access to a record may within thirty days appeal in writing  such denial to the head, chief executive or governing body of the entity, or the  person therefore designated by such head, chief executive, or governing body, who  shall within ten business days of the receipt of such appeal fully explain in writing to the person requesting the record the reasons for further denial, or provide access to the record sought.” 

I am requesting that you either fulfill this FOIL request, or else provide a full explanation as to the reason for the denial of this public record.

Sincerely,
Chris Gelardi

title: Public Records Request for Data on School Policing (Williamstown Police Department)

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Public Records Request for Data on School Policing (Williamstown Police Department)
communications.communication:
To whoever it may concern: 

This letter constitutes a request pursuant to the Public Records Act, G.L. c.66, §10, for public records in the custody of your school district. Under the Criminal Justice Reform Act,  school districts and law enforcement agencies must “specify the manner and division of responsibility for collecting and reporting the school-based arrests, citations and court referrals of students to the Department of Elementary and Secondary Education” (DESE).   DESE began collecting data on school-related arrests in the 2018-19 school year. In the 2019-20 school year, DESE has expanded that collection to include data on all referrals to law enforcement.  DESE has defined these terms as follows, borrowing the same definitions used by the U.S. Department of Education since its 2009 Civil Rights Data Collection.  

A school-related arrest “[r]efers to an arrest of a student for any activity conducted on school grounds, during off campus school activities (including while taking school transportation), or due to a referral by any school official. All school-related arrests are considered referrals to law enforcement.”  

A referral to law enforcement “[i]s an action by which a student is reported to any law enforcement agency or official, including a school police unit, for an incident that occurs on school grounds, during school-related events, or while taking school transportation, regardless of whether official action is taken. Citations, tickets, court referrals, and school-related arrests are considered referrals to law enforcement.”   


I request the following public records, as defined in G. L. c. 4, § 7 (twenty-sixth): 

1.	An extract of your records management system or database that includes each school-related arrest and each referral to law enforcement conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022 school year (up until the day the records are produced). Specifically, we request an extract of the database to include the following columns:
a.	Date of arrest or referral to law enforcement
b.	Time of arrest or referral to law enforcement
c.	Charge (or charges)
d.	Whether the individual(s) was arrested or referred to law enforcement
e.	Sex of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
f.	Age of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
g.	Race of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
h.	Ethnicity of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
i.	Disability status of the individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
j.	Whether the individual arrested or referred to law enforcement is a student at the school.
k.	Name of arresting officer, if applicable, and 
l.	Badge number of the arresting officer or the officer that referred the youth to law enforcement, as applicable.

2.	If such an extract of the database in question 1 is not possible, please provide school incident reports on each school-related arrest and referral to law enforcement conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022 school year (up until the day the records are produced). 

3.	A copy of any active standard operating procedures developed with the police department and/or other law enforcement agencies regarding police placement or activity in your corresponding school;  and,

4.	Any records instructing or informing police personnel of, or otherwise describing data reporting requirements and procedures for complying with G.L. c. 71 § 37P(b).

5.	The cost to the school district of assigning a school resource officer to each school; and, 

6.	The total number of school resource officers and total number of guidance counselors for each school in your district for school years 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and,

7.	The total number and a brief description of 911 calls from schools in your district to local police departments conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022, and, 

8.	A description of the proposed budget for mental, social, or emotional health support personnel for the school district.

As this request involves a matter of public interest and will not be used for any commercial purpose, we ask that all fees associated with this request be waived pursuant to 950 C.M.R. 32.07(2)(k). The purpose of this request is to determine whether your school district and police department are complying with their reporting obligations under the Criminal Justice Reform Act.  “The public has an interest in knowing whether public servants are carrying out their duties in an efficient and law-abiding manner.”    

It would be ill-advised to impose a fee for data that your school district may have failed to report in violation of statutory and regulatory duty.  Moreover, as you know, municipalities with a population of over 20,000 may not assess a fee for the first 2 hours of time spent searching for, compiling, segregating, redacting and reproducing a requested record. Finally, pursuant to 950 C.M.R. 32.07(2)(i), a records access officer shall assess no fee greater than the lowest hourly rate of a person capable of compiling, segregating, redacting and reproducing a requested record. In the event that a charge is incurred for this request which you will not waive, please so indicate and include an itemization of estimated good faith costs.
 
Please provide public records to a requestor in an electronic format unless the record is not available in an electronic format. G.L.c. 66, § 6A(d). 

The Public Records Act requires that you comply with this request within ten (10) business days following receipt. If you believe that documents or data responsive to any request herein is not public record and thus not subject to disclosure, please set forth in writing the specific reasons for such assertion, including the specific exemption or exemptions that you believe apply.  To the extent that you determine that records need to be redacted in order to be produced under any law protecting the privacy of named individuals, please do so rather than withholding them in their entirety.

If you have any questions about this request, or need additional time to respond, please contact me by phone at (617)-373-5862 or by email at k.stathulis@northeastern.edu. Thank you in advance for your prompt response to this request.
	
Sincerely, 


Katherine Stathulis, Esq.
Center for Public Interest, Advocacy, and Collaboration
Northeastern University School of Law

Hello Nicole,

On behalf of Katherine, thank you for emailing us referrals/arrest information in response to our public record request on January 11th.
Could you please also send us:
“a copy of any active memorandum of agreement between your police department and local school districts regarding police placement or activity in schools” (MOU) and
“a copy of any active standard operating procedures developed with the police department and/or other law enforcement agencies regarding police placement or activity in your corresponding school” (SOP)?

If you do not have possession or custody of these two items, would you be able to give us a contact and email at the school department who would be able to assist us in this matter?

Thank you,
Meghan Leong
Center for Public Interest, Advocacy, and Collaboration
Northeastern University School of Law

Hello Meghan,

Attached is the memorandum of understanding between the police department and local school districts. There are no responsive documents to the second part of this request: pertaining to "any active standard operating procedures developed regarding police placement or activity in school (SOP)." This last file completes the request. 

Thank you,

Nicole Beverly
Town Clerk & Records Access Officer

title: Mitchell Rogovin

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Mitchell Rogovin
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records mentioning, relating to, or generated as a result of investigation or inquiry of Mitchell Rogovin. (December 3, 1930 - February 7, 1996). Proof of death is not required as his death was widely reported: https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=950CE2D61439F93BA35751C0A960958260

Please conduct a search of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Indices, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, for both main-file records and cross-reference records for all relevant names, individuals, agencies and companies at FBI Headquarters. Please also conduct a search for records at the Alexandria Records Center. If any potentially responsive records have been destroyed and/or transferred to NARA, then I request copies of the destruction or transfer slips as well as any other documentation relating to, mentioning or describing said transfer or destruction, to include but not be limited to confirmation that the Bureau has no other copies of said records. If previously released records are available, then I request a rolling release consisting of those records while additional records are located and processed for release.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Paul Galante

title: Public Records Request for Data on School Policing (Nantucket Police Department)

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Public Records Request for Data on School Policing (Nantucket Police Department)
communications.communication:
To whoever it may concern: 

This letter constitutes a request pursuant to the Public Records Act, G.L. c.66, §10, for public records in the custody of your school district. Under the Criminal Justice Reform Act,  school districts and law enforcement agencies must “specify the manner and division of responsibility for collecting and reporting the school-based arrests, citations and court referrals of students to the Department of Elementary and Secondary Education” (DESE).   DESE began collecting data on school-related arrests in the 2018-19 school year. In the 2019-20 school year, DESE has expanded that collection to include data on all referrals to law enforcement.  DESE has defined these terms as follows, borrowing the same definitions used by the U.S. Department of Education since its 2009 Civil Rights Data Collection.  

A school-related arrest “[r]efers to an arrest of a student for any activity conducted on school grounds, during off campus school activities (including while taking school transportation), or due to a referral by any school official. All school-related arrests are considered referrals to law enforcement.”  

A referral to law enforcement “[i]s an action by which a student is reported to any law enforcement agency or official, including a school police unit, for an incident that occurs on school grounds, during school-related events, or while taking school transportation, regardless of whether official action is taken. Citations, tickets, court referrals, and school-related arrests are considered referrals to law enforcement.”   


I request the following public records, as defined in G. L. c. 4, § 7 (twenty-sixth): 

1.	An extract of your records management system or database that includes each school-related arrest and each referral to law enforcement conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022 school year (up until the day the records are produced). Specifically, we request an extract of the database to include the following columns:
a.	Date of arrest or referral to law enforcement
b.	Time of arrest or referral to law enforcement
c.	Charge (or charges)
d.	Whether the individual(s) was arrested or referred to law enforcement
e.	Sex of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
f.	Age of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
g.	Race of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
h.	Ethnicity of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
i.	Disability status of the individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
j.	Whether the individual arrested or referred to law enforcement is a student at the school.
k.	Name of arresting officer, if applicable, and 
l.	Badge number of the arresting officer or the officer that referred the youth to law enforcement, as applicable.

2.	If such an extract of the database in question 1 is not possible, please provide school incident reports on each school-related arrest and referral to law enforcement conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022 school year (up until the day the records are produced). 

3.	A copy of any active standard operating procedures developed with the police department and/or other law enforcement agencies regarding police placement or activity in your corresponding school;  and,

4.	Any records instructing or informing police personnel of, or otherwise describing data reporting requirements and procedures for complying with G.L. c. 71 § 37P(b).

5.	The cost to the school district of assigning a school resource officer to each school; and, 

6.	The total number of school resource officers and total number of guidance counselors for each school in your district for school years 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and,

7.	The total number and a brief description of 911 calls from schools in your district to local police departments conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022, and, 

8.	A description of the proposed budget for mental, social, or emotional health support personnel for the school district.

As this request involves a matter of public interest and will not be used for any commercial purpose, we ask that all fees associated with this request be waived pursuant to 950 C.M.R. 32.07(2)(k). The purpose of this request is to determine whether your school district and police department are complying with their reporting obligations under the Criminal Justice Reform Act.  “The public has an interest in knowing whether public servants are carrying out their duties in an efficient and law-abiding manner.”    

It would be ill-advised to impose a fee for data that your school district may have failed to report in violation of statutory and regulatory duty.  Moreover, as you know, municipalities with a population of over 20,000 may not assess a fee for the first 2 hours of time spent searching for, compiling, segregating, redacting and reproducing a requested record. Finally, pursuant to 950 C.M.R. 32.07(2)(i), a records access officer shall assess no fee greater than the lowest hourly rate of a person capable of compiling, segregating, redacting and reproducing a requested record. In the event that a charge is incurred for this request which you will not waive, please so indicate and include an itemization of estimated good faith costs.
 
Please provide public records to a requestor in an electronic format unless the record is not available in an electronic format. G.L.c. 66, § 6A(d). 

The Public Records Act requires that you comply with this request within ten (10) business days following receipt. If you believe that documents or data responsive to any request herein is not public record and thus not subject to disclosure, please set forth in writing the specific reasons for such assertion, including the specific exemption or exemptions that you believe apply.  To the extent that you determine that records need to be redacted in order to be produced under any law protecting the privacy of named individuals, please do so rather than withholding them in their entirety.

If you have any questions about this request, or need additional time to respond, please contact me by phone at (617)-373-5862 or by email at k.stathulis@northeastern.edu. Thank you in advance for your prompt response to this request.
	
Sincerely, 


Katherine Stathulis, Esq.
Center for Public Interest, Advocacy, and Collaboration
Northeastern University School of Law

Dear Requestor,

We apologize for the delay but we are still working on your request. Under the Freedom of Information Act, a public body may extend the time to respond to a FOIA request by up to 5 business days for a limited number of reasons. Under Section 140/3(e), the Park District is extending the time to respond to your request by five business days from the last due date for the following reasons:

(x ) the requested records are stored in whole or in part at other locations than the office having charge of the requested records;
( ) the request requires the collection of a substantial number of specified records;
( ) the request is couched in categorical terms and requires an extensive search for the records responsive to it;
( ) the requested records have not been located in the course of routine search and additional efforts are being made to locate them;
(x) the requested records require examination and evaluation by personnel having the necessary competence and discretion to determine if they are exempt from disclosure under Section 7 of this Act or should be revealed only with appropriate deletions;
( ) the request for records cannot be complied with by the public body within the time limits prescribed by subsection (d) of this Section without unduly burdening or interfering with the operations of the public body;
( ) there is a need for consultation, which shall be conducted with all practicable speed, with another public body or among 2 or more components of a public body having a substantial interest in the determination or in the subject matter of the request.

If this is acceptable to you, please respond in writing to agree to this extension. The new due date for your request is Monday February 5, 2024 by close of business.

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: USGS drone footage of prescribed burns
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting images and video recorded in drone flyovers of prescribed burns in "USGS (Wetland Aquatic Research Center)" and "USGS Wetland Aquatic Research Center Lafayette LA" on January 26, 2023.

This mission was disclosed in a log of drone missions released via a previous FOIA request. The remote pilots in command are listed as Stephen B. Hartley and William R. Jones.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ben Welsh

communications.subject: FOIA:  DOI-USGS-2023-004942:  Acknowledgment of your FOIA request
communications.communication:
Dear Mr. Welsh:

"On June 6, 2023, the U.S. Geological Survey (USGS) Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) office received your FOIA request dated June 6, 2023, and assigned it control number DOI-USGS-2023-004942.  Please cite this number in any future communications with our office regarding your request.  You request the following information:

I am requesting images and video recorded in drone flyovers of prescribed burns in "USGS (Wetland Aquatic Research Center)" and "USGS Wetland Aquatic Research Center Lafayette LA" on January 26, 2023.

We have classified you as a representative of the “news media” requester.  As such, we may charge you for some of our duplication costs, but we will not charge you for our search or review costs; you also are entitled to up to 100 pages of photocopies (or an equivalent volume) for free.  See 43 C.F.R. § 2.39.  If, after taking into consideration your fee category entitlements, our processing costs are less than $50.00, we will not bill you because the cost of collection would be greater than the fee collected.  See 43 C.F.R. § 2.49(a)(1).  You can expect to hear from us promptly regarding the outcome of this search.

You have agreed to pay up to $200.00 for the processing of your request.  If we find that this will not cover the cost of processing your request, we will stop processing your request at the point this amount has been reached and will let you know before we incur additional charges.  You can then either agree to pay the additional amount needed or narrow the scope of your request.

We use Multitrack Processing to process FOIA requests.  The Simple track is for requests that would generally take one to five workdays to process.  The Normal track is for requests that would generally take six to twenty workdays to process.  The Complex track is for requests that would generally take twenty-one to sixty workdays to process.  The Extraordinary track is for requests that would generally take more than sixty workdays to process.  The Expedited track is for requests that have been granted expedited processing, which are processed as soon as practicable.  Within each track, requests are usually processed on a first-in, first-out basis.

Your request falls into the Normal processing track.  There are 15 requests pending ahead of yours in our overall processing queue.  Presuming that our current FOIA capacity and burden remain constant, we expect that we will dispatch a determination to you by July 10, 2023.

You may narrow the scope of your request to obtain quicker processing in your currently-assigned track or move the request into a different track, which may enable us to process it more quickly by communicating with us at foia@usgs.gov.

The 2007 FOIA amendments created the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) to offer mediation services to resolve disputes between FOIA requesters and Federal agencies as a non-exclusive alternative to litigation.  Using OGIS services does not affect your right to pursue litigation.  You may contact OGIS in any of the following ways:            

Office of Government Information Services

National Archives and Records Administration

8601 Adelphi Road - OGIS

College Park, MD  20740-6001

Telephone:  (202) 741-5770

Fax:  (202) 741-5769

Toll-free:  1 (877) 684-6448

E-mail:  ogis@nara.gov

Web: https://www.archives.gov/ogis

Please note that using OGIS services does not affect the timing of an appeal with the Department’s FOIA & Privacy Act Appeals Officer. Contact information for the Department’s FOIA Public Liaison, who you may also seek dispute resolution services from, is available at https://www.doi.gov/foia/foiacenters.

If you have any questions about your request, you may contact me by email at foia@usgs.gov.

Sincerely,

Eric J. Darby

Government FOIA Analyst"

title: Bellevue Washington School District #408 - REQUEST FOR COMMUNICATIONS AND WRITINGS of District Leadership Team, current and former Superintendents, and School Board

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Bellevue Washington School District #408 - REQUEST FOR COMMUNICATIONS AND WRITINGS of District Leadership Team, current and former Superintendents, and School Board
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern - Bellevue School District #408 :

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act [Chapter 42.56 RCW] I hereby request the following records:

REQUEST FOR COMMUNICATIONS AND WRITINGS – PUBLIC RECORDS REQUEST FOR ALL 	ELECTRONIC MAIL (E-MAIL), ELECTRONIC TEXTS, TELEPHONE COMMUNICATIONS, TELEPHONE MESSAGES, AND TELEPHONE LOGS of the following individuals for the period of time between January 1, 2019 – November 2, 2021:

Superintendent Dr. Ivan Duran
Superintendent Dr. Art Jarvis
Assistant Superintendent Human Resources, Jeff Thomas 
Executive Director for District and Community Affairs, John Harrison
Director of Research, Evaluation and Assessment Naomi Calvo
Deputy Superintendent Student Academic Performance and Instructional Leadership, Eva Collins
Deputy Superintendent Finance and Operations, Melissa deVita
Chief Communications and Engagement Officer, Janine Thorn
District 1 School Board Member Sima Sarrafa
District 2 School Board Member Carolyn Watson
District 3 School Board Member Erica Melief
District 4 School Board Member Christine Chew
District 5 School Board Member Francine Wiest
Director of Program Office, Melanie McGee
Director Equity and Strategic Engagement, Shomari Jones
Executive Director Teaching and Learning, Sharon Kautz
Executive Director Teaching and Learning, Heather Edlund
Executive Director of Schools, Patty Siegwarth
Executive Director of Schools, Kelly Aramaki
Executive Director of Schools, Heather Sánchez
Executive Director of Schools, Gloria Henderson

With respect to requests for records that include "communications," I am requesting all emails, text messages, and telephone records, regardless the type of device or account from which the communication was generated or where the device or data is stored (including personal devices such as personal cell phones, laptops, tablets, and/or computers etc. used from home to conduct public business during the COVID-19 Pandemic). Nissen v. Pierce County, 183 Wa.2d 863 (2015).

With respect to requests for records that include "Writings" per 42.56.010(4) this means handwriting, typewriting, printing, photostating, photographing, and every other means of recording any form of communication or representation including, but not limited to, letters, words, pictures, sounds, or symbols, or combination thereof, and all papers, maps, magnetic or paper tapes, photographic films and prints, motion picture, film and video recordings, magnetic or punched cards, discs, drums, diskettes, sound recordings, and other documents including existing data compilations from which information may be obtained or translated.

This request specifically includes - and the District is specifically directed to obtain, preserve in native format, and produce - any records pertaining to public business that exist on any computers, hard drives, portable phones, jump drives, BlackBerries, iPhone, Kindle, IPad, or other devices, or in email, data, voice mail, or text mail accounts owned, controlled or paid for, directly or indirectly, by any agency or 3rd party. 

In the event the District chooses to provide the records in installments over time I request the records to be produced in reverse chronological order - from the most recent to the earliest.

If this request is denied in whole or part, I ask that you justify all deletions by reference to specific exemptions of the PRA. I also request  a detailed contemporaneous log to be provided for any document withheld or redacted.

For each responsive record the District contends is exempt from public disclosure, in whole or in part, please specifically identify the record by subject, title, author, custodian and date, and state how a specific statutory exemption applies to each record as required by RCW 42.56.210(3) and Rental Housing Ass'n v. Des Moines, 165 Wn.2d 525, 199 P.3d 393 (2009).

I request electronic production of all records in the original NATIVE electronic format for each record. 

For emails I request production of emails in native MICROSOFT .pst (personal storage table) format which allows for a virtually infinite number of emails to be produced in a single digital file, providing for economy and convenience. If the .pst format is not available, I would request production of email in .pdf (portable document format) another widely accepted format for email production providing similar economy and convenience of a virtually infinite number emails bundled  into a single digital .pdf file. 

I request records production by public (no password) e-mail attachment or link if available or USB DRIVE or CD-ROM if not.

THIS REQUEST IS NOT BEING MADE FOR COMMERCIAL PURPOSES.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

BHS Wolverines

To Whom It May Concern:

I wanted to follow up on the following Washington Public Records Act request, copied below, and originally submitted on Nov. 2, 2021. Please let me know when I can expect to receive a response.

Thanks for your help, and let me know if further clarification is needed.

communications.subject: PRR 11022021-Anon
communications.communication:
PRR 11022021-Anon (NOTE: please refer to this number in all correspondence regarding your request)
Dear Anonymous requestor:
On behalf of the Bellevue School District, I acknowledge receipt of your request as follows:

REQUEST FOR COMMUNICATIONS AND WRITINGS – PUBLIC RECORDS REQUEST FOR ALL ELECTRONIC MAIL (E-MAIL), ELECTRONIC TEXTS, TELEPHONE COMMUNICATIONS, TELEPHONE MESSAGES, AND TELEPHONE LOGS of the following individuals for the period of time between January 1, 2019 – November 2, 2021:

Superintendent Dr. Ivan Duran
Superintendent Dr. Art Jarvis
Assistant Superintendent Human Resources, Jeff Thomas
Executive Director for District and Community Affairs, John Harrison
Director of Research, Evaluation and Assessment Naomi Calvo
Deputy Superintendent Student Academic Performance and Instructional Leadership, Eva Collins
Deputy Superintendent Finance and Operations, Melissa deVita
Chief Communications and Engagement Officer, Janine Thorn
District 1 School Board Member Sima Sarrafa
District 2 School Board Member Carolyn Watson
District 3 School Board Member Erica Melief
District 4 School Board Member Christine Chew
District 5 School Board Member Francine Wiest
Director of Program Office, Melanie McGee
Director Equity and Strategic Engagement, Shomari Jones
Executive Director Teaching and Learning, Sharon Kautz
Executive Director Teaching and Learning, Heather Edlund
Executive Director of Schools, Patty Siegwarth
Executive Director of Schools, Kelly Aramaki
Executive Director of Schools, Heather Sánchez
Executive Director of Schools, Gloria Henderson
Clarification Questions:

  1.  Your request seeks communications “of” the above -named individuals. Please define what you intend by “of.” A reasonable interpretation of that would be that you are seeking records “from” the above individuals. Are you also seeking records “to” the above-named persons? Are you seeking communications on which the above persons were cc’d?
  2.  I assume you intended to refer to School Board Member Sima Sarrafan. Please correct me if I am mistaken.
  3.  It is apparent that your request seeks a very substantial body of records. In the District’s efforts to serve you fully and as efficiently as possible, please consider specifying particular records of interest to you, or at the very least prioritize the records you are seeking in some way that will assist you in determining whether in fact you need all of the records described. For example, you could specify a topic, keywords, or a more narrow date range. You could specify a more targeted group of records to be produced first, while retaining the broader request in case it is needed.

Requestors are required to specify records requested so they are reasonably locatable. While the records you have described are locatable, the volume is extensive. The volume will affect the time required to produce the records.

  1.  I will assume at this time, consistent with the purposes of the Public Records Act, that you are seeking records that are meaningful to you regarding the conduct of the District, and for a legitimate purpose that will not interfere with the efficient administration of the District. Although you are not required under the law to disclose that purpose, I invite you to do so, so that I can assist you in targeting your request to that purpose. If your request is targeted, it will be much easier for you to find records that are meaningful to you within the body of produced records.
  2.  I recognize in this regard that you are requesting more recent records be produced first. Please be advised that it may be possible to honor that request within a body of records of a certain type (such as emails). It may not always be possible to do so consistently across all record types, due to differences in how different types of records are assembled.

In that regard, please specify a date range that you regard as “recent.” For example, are you requesting that the last 6 months of records be produced for all of the persons named above before any earlier records are produced for any other person, at least within a certain type of record? Please be advised that while the District will try to honor your preferences, the District will retain flexibility in this regard in order to process your request most efficiently.



Your answers to the above clarification questions are due on or before December 9, 2021.



Timing of Response

Your request will be completed in a series of installments. At this time, subject to potential adjustment based on your clarifications, I estimate a first installment of records for January 19, 2022. That present estimate is  based on the current workload in this office, staff available to respond to your request, the workload of staff who may be affected by your request and whose assistance may be required, and absences due to illness and/or the anticipated holidays. Response date estimates are subject to change.
Best regards,

Helen A. Boyer
Public Records Officer
Bellevue School District No. 405
425-456-4101
publicrecords@bsd405.org<mailto:publicrecords@bsd405.org>

communications.subject: RE: Washington Public Records Act Request #11022021
communications.communication:
PRR 11022021-Anon
Dear Anonymous requestor:
Clarification Questions (repeated and follow-ups):

1.                   Regarding clarification question 1:
“Please define what you intend by “of.” A reasonable interpretation of that would be that you are seeking records “from” the above individuals.”
Your answer included this comment:
Regarding the requested public record communications "of" and "from" the previously referenced individuals . . ..
It appears that your answer is that you intend “of” to mean “from.” The District will proceed in that manner unless you advise otherwise.

2.                   Please allow me to explain that In general, email records of each of the named individuals will be searched and produced separately by individual. Some of the search results may be combined in order to avoid a high number of duplications.  The District will retain discretion in this regard in order to process your request most efficiently.
Assuming separate production sets for each individual and some combined groups as appropriate, please advise if you would like to prioritize the individuals listed. The District will try to honor any such priorities, within parameters that are consistent with the most efficient processing of your request.

3.                   You have asked for records to be produced in reverse chronological order, stating that you prefer the District to produce emails first. To clarify, are you asking that all email records back to 1.1.19 for an individual be produced before any records are produced for another individual?

4.                   You did not respond to the questions numbered 3 and 4 (renumbered below due to formatting loss in your reply message) regarding targeting your request. As noted, targeting does not limit your request. Rather, it allows you to prioritize so that the records which will be most meaningful to you in support of your purpose will be produced to you before others. I understand this may be important to you in view of the volume of records you are requesting. For example, in searches performed to date, the number of potentially responsive emails from one individual was 38,743.  Others were in the 28,000 to 36,000 range.



I would be glad to discuss your request with you if it would be helpful. I am often able to help requestors target their requests when I have a better understanding of their priorities.

Please be advised that production of emails in .pst format is not possible. Every record is reviewed for applicable exemptions, and appropriate redactions will be applied prior to the production of records to you. The redaction process occurs only in a .pdf format. Each individual message is converted to a .pdf format.

Your answers to these questions are due on or before December 17, 2021. The timing of your answers may affect the timing of the District’s responses to your request. Additional clarification questions may arise in the course of responding to your request.

I am glad to assist you in accessing records that will be meaningful to you.
Best regards,

Helen A. Boyer
Public Records Officer
Bellevue School District No. 405
425-456-4101
publicrecords@bsd405.org<mailto:publicrecords@bsd405.org>

communications.subject: PRR 11022021-Anon RE: Washington Public Records Act Request #11022021
communications.communication:
PRR 11022021-Anon
Dear Requestor:
Thank you for the prompt response. Getting clarification of your request is important, to be sure we have a mutual understanding.

Clarification Questions

  1.  I still do not understand what you mean by the phrase “communications . . . of” an individual:

ALL email communications (any “to” or “from” address fields are irrelevant) of the following individuals . . . .

Every email is to or from someone. The address fields “to” or “from” are relevant because an archive search can be conducted using search fields “from/to/cc”,  “from”, or “to/cc.”  There is no search that can be conducted for communications “of” an individual. Please clarify what you intend by “communications of” an individual and by your statement that “any ‘to’ or ‘from’ address fields are irrelevant.”


  1.  I again note that you have not responded to clarification questions 3 and 4  in my November 9, 2021 message. Also, you deleted that November 9, 2021 message, and your November 8, 2021 message, from the correspondence history below. communications.subject: PRR 10122021-Anon RE: Washington Public Records Act Request #11022021
communications.communication:
PRR 10122021-Anon
Dear Anonymous requestor:
Thank you.
Clarification questions:

  1.  When you use the phrase communications “of” an individual, are you referring to:

  1.  communications “from” that individual? Please answer yes or no.

When you use the phrase communications “of” an individual, are you referring to:

  1.  communications “to” that individual? Please answer yes or no.

When you use the phrase communications “of” an individual, are you referring to:

  1.  communications “copied to” that individual? Please answer yes or no.



  1.  You have not responded to the following questions sent to you on 11.9.21, numbered 3 and 4 in that message. This is the District’s third request for a response to these questions:


3.       It is apparent that your request seeks a very substantial body of records. In the District’s efforts to serve you fully and as efficiently as possible, please consider specifying particular records of interest to you, or at the very least prioritize the records you are seeking in some way that will assist you in determining whether in fact you need all of the records described. For example, you could specify a topic, keywords, or a more narrow date range. You could specify a more targeted group of records to be produced first, while retaining the broader request in case it is needed.

Requestors are required to specify records requested so they are reasonably locatable. While the records you have described are locatable, the volume is extensive. The volume will affect the time required to produce the records.

4.       I will assume at this time, consistent with the purposes of the Public Records Act, that you are seeking records that are meaningful to you regarding the conduct of the District, and for a legitimate purpose that will not interfere with the efficient administration of the District. Although you are not required under the law to disclose that purpose, I invite you to do so, so that I can assist you in targeting your request to that purpose. If your request is targeted, it will be much easier for you to find records that are meaningful to you within the body of produced records.


In reminding you om 11.17.21 to respond to questions 3 and 4, I explained the importance to you of your answering these questions:

As noted, targeting does not limit your request. Rather, it allows you to prioritize so that the records which will be most meaningful to you in support of your purpose will be produced to you before others. I understand this may be important to you in view of the volume of records you are requesting. For example, in searches performed to date, the number of potentially responsive emails from one individual was 38,743. Others were in the 28,000 to 36,000 range.

I would be glad to discuss your request with you if it would be helpful. I am often able to help requestors target their requests when I have a better understanding of their priorities.
Thank you for clarifying your request at the outset. It is essential that we have a mutual understanding. Additional clarifications may arise in the course of processing your request. Your answers to the questions above are due on or before December 17, 2021. The timing of your answers will affect the timing of the District’s response.

Missing correspondence history
Please review the message you sent on 11.19.21 at 1:39 PM, and the message you sent on 11.18.21. In each of those messages, portions of the correspondence history between you and this office were missing, including but not limited to the 11.9.21 message to you containing the clarification questions above, to which you have not yet responded.
Perhaps this is a technical aberration of the service you are using. If necessary, please work with Muckrock to determine why portions of correspondence history related to your request may not be retained when you reply to a message. For example, your 11.19.21 message immediately below contains a history that skips from your message dated 11.02.21 to your message dated 11.11.21. Please take steps to prevent that from occurring in the future.


Public Records Request Process

You state:

“No search need be conducted – archive or copy the entire email account for the dates requested and produce the result preferably in .PST format.”



Please allow me to help you understand public record response procedures, so that your expectations can be realistic. When a request for records is made, the District conducts a search for potentially responsive records. When potentially responsive records are assembled, each record is reviewed to determine whether it is responsive, and if so, whether the law requires that exemptions be applied to it. If some or all of a record is exempt, the District applies redactions to that record or withholds it, and then describes to the requestor the basis for any exemptions that were applied. As noted below, it is not possible to produce records in .PST format, because records must first be converted to .PDF format in order to apply redactions to them.

For these reasons, it is not possible to “copy” the contents of “an entire email account” and produce all emails within such a an account to you. Each email must first be reviewed, analyzed, and processed for production.

As noted in my 11.09.021 message to you, your request will be completed in a series of installments. Due to the procedures described above, only a limited number of email records can be produced per installment. Each request is unique, but given the workload of this office, email records can be generally processed at a rate of perhaps 30-100 individual emails per installment. Installments may occur at varying intervals, which can be 30 days or more. These processing volume rates vary widely based on the nature of the request and other factors.
As stated above, during the nearly 3-year period you have identified, one of the persons on your list sent 38,743 emails—that is 38,743 emails were “from” that person. There may be some duplications within that number. However, even if that number was significantly reduced to something in the range of 20,000 emails, and assuming a rate of processing those records at 100 per month, it could take 200 months, or more than 16 years, to process only the emails “from” that one person on your list.

I am taking the time to explain this to you in detail, at the beginning of processing your request, so that you can understand how important it is to you, assuming your intention is to receive records that are meaningful to you and relate to a legitimate purpose, to limit your request by targeting it in some way as described in questions 3 and 4 above. I can help you find the needle in the haystack that you really want. You do not need to ask for the haystack to achieve your legitimate purpose.

I am available to assist you in exploring options by which you can limit your request so that it will yield records that will be meaningful to you, while retaining your broader request in case it is needed.
Best regards,

Helen A. Boyer
Public Records Officer
Bellevue School District No. 405
425-456-4101
publicrecords@bsd405.org<mailto:publicrecords@bsd405.org>

To give you a sense of the volume of records you have requested, searches of potentially responsive records for the following persons for the first six-month period, 05 01 21 through 11 02 21, returned the following numbers of potentially responsive messages to be reviewed and processed for production to you:

Superintendent Dr. Ivan Duran                                                                   8420
Superintendent Dr. Art Jarvis                                                                      7245
Assistant Superintendent Human Resources, Jeff Thomas              25,244

NOTE: I am having technical difficulties creating this link. I will complete this process as soon as possible.

For example, you could consider redefining “communications of” to mean “to” or “from” but not “cc”; limiting the date range; limiting the request to one or more topics of interest; identifying key words; and/or agreeing that commercial solicitations, newsletters, and subscriptions would not be responsive.

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request #11022021, Installment 2
communications.communication:
PRR 11022021-Anon
Dear Requestor:
On behalf of the Bellevue School District, I am making a second installment in response to your request for records. You requested emails to be produced in reverse chron order, in 6 month blocks, to/from/cc the following persons in this following order:

Superintendent Dr. Ivan Duran
Superintendent Dr. Art Jarvis
Assistant Superintendent Human Resources, Jeff Thomas
Chief Communications and Engagement Officer, Janine Thorn
Director Equity and Strategic Engagement, Shomari Jones
Executive Director for District and Community Affairs, John Harrison
Director of Research, Evaluation and Assessment Naomi Calvo
Deputy Superintendent Student Academic Performance and Instructional Leadership, Eva Collins
Deputy Superintendent Finance and Operations, Melissa deVita
District 1 School Board Member Sima Sarrafan
District 2 School Board Member Carolyn Watson
District 3 School Board Member Erica Melief
District 4 School Board Member Christine Chew
District 5 School Board Member Francine Wiest
Director of Program Office, Melanie McGee
Executive Director Teaching and Learning, Sharon Kautz
Executive Director Teaching and Learning, Heather Edlund
Executive Director of Schools, Patty Siegwarth
Executive Director of Schools, Kelly Aramaki
Executive Director of Schools, Heather Sánchez
Executive Director of Schools, Gloria Henderson
This installment includes emails to/from/cc Superintendent Ivan Duran for the period 10 15 21 through 10 21 2021. It includes 227 messages. The period 10 22 2021 through 11 02 2021 will be the subject of the next installment.

The records are being produced to you via Box, from which you may retrieve, view, and download records, within 30 days of receipt. A link will be provided to you to access the records in a message that will follow shortly.

Please note that Dr. Duran has not been employed by the District since the spring of 2021. As a result, there are no messages from him in this group. The vast majority of messages are commercial solicitations, newsletters or subscriptions; messages on which Dr. Duran was copied because his name may not have yet been deleted from a distribution group; or messages from persons who did not know of his status.

Your request could be completed more efficiently if you limited the volume of potentially responsive records to retrieve messages that are more likely to be of interest to you. This could be accomplished in a number of ways. For example, you could consider redefining “communications of” to mean “to” or “from” but not “cc”; limiting the number of persons whose communications are sought; limiting the date range; limiting the request to one or more topics of interest; identifying key words; and/or agreeing that commercial solicitations, newsletters, and subscriptions would not be responsive.

Redactions were made to one record in this set, consistent with exemptions set forth in the Public Records Act. Redactions are indicated by blocked out text with an overlying code. I have also attached to this message a Redaction and Exemption Codes chart that explains the basis for the exemptions that applied.  If there are any records that contain marked out texts that do not have an overlying code, that is the form in which the record was received by the District.

I estimate the next installment for March 30, 2022.
In order to expedite the District’s response to your request, please consider limiting the request to a reasonable volume that is more likely to be of interest to you, as suggested above.
Best regards,

Helen A. Boyer
Public Records Officer
Bellevue School District No. 405
425-456-4101
publicrecords@bsd405.org<mailto:publicrecords@bsd405.org>

communications.subject: RE: Washington Public Records Act Request #11022021
communications.communication:
PRR 11022021-Anon-Muckrock
Dear Requestor:
The Bellevue School District is not withholding any records from you.
Please direct all messages pertaining to your request to the public records mailbox, publicrecords@bsd405.org.
The automated correspondence features of the Muckrock site are not an efficient way to correspond or to review correspondence. Please do not interrupt our correspondence history by cutting messages out of the email string. I know that history can get long. However, it is important in order for us to communicate effectively that an accurate history of our communications is readily available to both of us.
Please allow me to summarize our recent correspondence:

Feb 25–email from BSD, making second installment consisting of 227 emails, and providing link to Box for records.
Feb 26—confirmation from Box site to BSD that you accepted and opened link to records.
June 29—email from you, stating you had received only one installment, on 1.9.22.
June 29–email from BSD, setting a next installment for July 21.
July 15—email from you, inquiring as to status. Appears to be automated Muckrock email. June 29 message from BSD does not appear to have been read.
July 21—email from BSD, inquiring further about your statement on June 29 that you had received only one installment, and listing two installments that were produced. Attached your 2.26.22 acceptance of link to second installment provided via Box site. Advised that estimated installment intended for July 21 would be extended to July 22.
July 25, 26, 28 – emails from BSD, extending estimated dates from July 22 to August 1, with explanations.
Aug 3–email from you, explaining (for the first time) that you were not able to open the link to records that were sent to you on 2.25.22.

Installment 2 Produced to You Again
First, let’s take care of your receipt of the records in the February 25 installment. You were advised in a February 25 email that a link to the records was on its way to you. I received confirmation on February 26 that you accepted and opened the link that was sent to you. Now, on August 3, you explain for the first time that you were not able to retrieve records in the link that was provided to you. If you had let me know in February that you had difficulty retrieving the records, we could have resolved it at that time. I recognize there may be glitches with technology. I am glad to work with you to resolve them promptly, if you let me know.

Each installment is made available to you for 30 days. In the future, if you do not acknowledge and accept receipt of records within 30 days after they are made available to you, your request will be closed as abandoned.

I am re-sending you the records that were provided to you in installment 2 on February 25, 2021. I will attach these to two emails to you, due to their volume.

Installment 2 consisted of 227 email records covering a period of October 15-21, 2021, in zip folders are follows:
2021 10 15_10 19, Duran, 122 (attached here)
2021 10 20_10 21, Duran, 105 (will be attached to an email that follows)

The second zip folder includes a record that contains information that is exempt from disclosure under the Public Records Act. Exempt information is redacted and marked with an overlay code. I will attach to the following email a Redaction and Exemption Codes chart that explains the basis of exemptions applied.

Progress on your high-volume request
Please appreciate the overall high volume of your request, when there are 227 email records in one week for one of your named recipients. Each individual email record you request must be retrieved from archives, reviewed for applicability to your request and for exemptions, and then prepared for production to you.
Due to typical operational capacity of this department, it is generally possible to process roughly 100 email records per installment, and to make installments to a requestor every 60 to 90 days. These are general capacity numbers, which may be adjusted in different contexts for different types of requests. Most requestors seek specific information that is likely to be meaningful to them, which allows for effective and efficient request processing.
Your request, on the other hand, seeks a high volume of communications, from a large group of persons, with no specific focus or topic. As a result, the volume of records will be is very high, the retrieval time is extensive, and the review process is very time-consuming.
You have been provided 446 records in installment 1, Jan 19 2022; and 227 records in installment 2, February 25 2022, for a total of 673 records. This is well within standard processing rate.

Next Estimated Installment
The District attempts to meet its estimated installment dates. Sometimes that is not possible. If it is not possible to meet an estimated date, you will be provided an explanation and a revised estimated date.
The time it took to complete today’s correspondence was time the District was not able to devote to a next installment to you.
I estimate a next installment for September 1, 2022. That estimate takes into account factors of summer staff absences; staff absences for other reasons, including medical leaves; the current workload of this department; and the complexity of assembly and review required for your request as set forth above.
Best regards,

Helen A. Boyer
Public Records Officer
Bellevue School District No. 405
425-456-4101
publicrecords@bsd405.org<mailto:publicrecords@bsd405.org>
